LINNAEUS's herbarium, which was the largest of its day and was gathered together by contributions from almost all con— temporary botanists and scientific explorers‚¹ fell after Linnaeus’s death to his son, Prof. Carl von Linne fil.

When the latter died in 1783, the herbarium was offered for sale by his mother and sisters as heirs, just as Linnaeus (pater) had appointed in his lifetime‚ partly on account of its high monetary value, partly because he did not consider his son sufficiently interested in botany to deserve this pre- cious heirloom of his father.
